\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be the target function, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be our hypothesis.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H[i]$
\end_inset

 is the probability of going to state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the given data, for simplicity every entry in the list D is an integer
 between 0 and the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula $D[i]$
\end_inset

 can be used like 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

).
 Additionally assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the data that leads to our prior (i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the data for a team in a given year, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the data for all teams for the last 2 decades, the standard matrix).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum H[i]=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P(H=F\mid D)=P(D\mid H=F)P(H=F)\div P(D)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(P(H=F\mid D))=max(P(D\mid H=F)P(H=F)\div P(D))=max(P(D\mid H=F)P(H=F))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P(D\mid H=F)=\prod H[D[i]]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P(H=F)=\prod H[S[i]]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the list of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 appended together.
 We can now write: 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D\mid H=F)P(H=F)=\prod H[D[i]]*\prod H[S[i]]=\prod H[V[i]]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore: 
\begin_inset Formula $max(P(H=F\mid D))=max(\prod H[V[i]])$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally maximizing a single set of multiplications has already been
 achieved when making the standard matrix, the same can be done to find
 
\begin_inset Formula $max(\prod H[V[i]])$
\end_inset

 (simply normalize the row with the appended data lists).
\end_layout

